l Hutchinson, Claire Pratt, and Anna Porter, and literary agent Bella Pomer made the most of their vocational prospects, first by securing their respective positions and then by refining their professional methods. Individually, each woman asserted her agency by adapting orthodox ways of working within Canadian publishing. Collectively, and perhaps more importantly, their overarching approach emerged more broadly as a feminist practice. Guided by the resolve to make industry-wide improvements, these women disrupted the dominant masculine paradigm and reinvigorated the culture of publishing and authorship in Canada. Through their vision and method these trailblazing women became agents of change who helped transform publishing practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aLiterary agentszOntariozTorontovBiography. 0aPublishers and publishingzCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen editorszOntariozTorontovBiography. 0aWomen in the book industries and tradezCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen in the book industries and tradezOntariozTorontovBiography. 0aWomen publisherszOntariozTorontovBiography. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aCanadian literature.  aanna porter.  afeminism.  ahistory of Canadian publishing.  atwentieth-century Canadian book publishing.  awomen editors.  awomen in Canadian publishing.  awomen literary agents.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781487